It has often been observed that this satire consists of two parts, which have little connexion with each other. The first begins by introducing Crispinus as the object of attach, and his vices are satirised (1—33); then follow three lines (34-36) as introduction to the main episode, in which Crispinus has only a passing mention (1. 108), while

the real subject is Domitianand his manner of behaviour to the high officials who formed his Privy Council. The poem is certainly ill- constructed; and Weidner concludes that we have here two satires of which the first was left unfinished. This may be so; but we have no reason for supposing that anyone other than the author originally brought them together to form one poem. See Introd. to Sat. 7.
